		<p class="quarter_padding_vertical">
			To make a striking impression, every item of your stationery should match perfectly, just like an outfit.</p>

		<p class="quarter_padding_vertical">
			Co-ordination is important because it shows care and attention to detail precisely because it takes more work and effort to make things compliment one another.
		</p>
		<p class="quarter_padding_vertical">
			Poor co-ordination shows thoughtlessness and neglect. </p>

		<p class="last">
			That's why every item in our stationery suite works in careful harmony with its siblings, from the ribbon, to the professionally tailored maps, to the tissue paper. Everything is beautifull co-ordinated to match, from the Save The Date cards to the Order
			of Service. </p>




















































				<h2 class="text_center width_large">
	 <img src="/images/homepage/icons/write.svg" style="padding-top:1em;display:inline-block;margin:0 auto;padding-bottom:0;margin-bottom:0;width:45px;" /><br/>
															Personalisation will save you many hours of valuable time and stress&hellip;

														</h2>
		<p class="quarter_padding_vertical">
			Have you any idea how long it takes to individually address each invitation and envelope?
		</p>

		<p class="quarter_padding_vertical">It's probably something you haven't thought too hard about, but handwriting guest names on each invitation is a messy, time consuming , physically demanding and error prone business&hellip;</p>

		<p class="quarter_padding_vertical">Your hand will ache after a while and the beautiful handwriting you inscribed on the first invitation will start looking like a Doctor's signature by invitation number 32.</p>

		<p class="quarter_padding_vertical">And there's no delete button when you mess up the spelling, and oh dear, now your invitation is ruined as the name won't fit in the space!</p>

		<p class="quarter_padding_vertical">If you're going to personalise your invitations by hand, then you need to be prepared to order a good few extra envelopes and invitations as you're going to screw up some of them. It's a fact. </p>

		<img src="/images/homepage/big_illustrations/guestname.png" style="margin:0 auto;width:250px;display:block;" />

		<p class="quarter_padding_vertical">Plus, ink smudges easily, and in the words of one of our brides, "I just don't like the look of a perfect printed invitation and then hand written names".</p>

		<p class="quarter_padding_vertical">But there's a simple solution:</p>

		<p class="quarter_padding_vertical">We can print your guest names on each invitation individually, as well as addressing your envelopes (more info below):</p>

		<img src="/images/homepage/big_illustrations/guestaddress.png" class="image_100" style="margin:0 auto;padding-top:1em;padding-bottom:1em;display:block;" />
		<p class="quarter_padding_vertical">not only does it look much nicer to have an invitation co-ordinated with pre-printed names in a matching font, but creating a list you can edit and update on a computer first is much more sensible:</p>

		<p class="quarter_padding_vertical">You can thorougly check for mistakes, and, if you intend to handwrite your envelopes you're going to have to create a list of names and addresses anyway&hellip;

		</p>

		<p class="quarter_padding_vertical">&hellip;so why, when you've already created the list, double the amount of time and effort by rewriting these all out when they can just be emailed to us for printing?</p>

		<p class="quarter_padding_vertical">But it's about more than just saving time&hellip;</p>

		<p class="quarter_padding_vertical">Personalisation is extremely important because by explicitly addressing your invitations to "Sarah, Jane & Jenny", it takes the guesswork away from your guests:</p>

		<p class="quarter_padding_vertical">Sarah knows straight away that she can bring her flatmate and daughter. If it just says "Sarah & Guest", she knows she is invited and can bring any guest.</p>

		<img src="/images/homepage/big_illustrations/monograms.png" class="image_100" style="display:block;margin:0 auto;" />
		<p class="quarter_padding_vertical">An invitation that isn't personalised makes it awkward for your guests to know who they can and can't bring along (and awkward for you to know who they are bringing along too), but if you address your guests individually, you'll make things easier for
			yourself and your guests from the start: it avoids that difficult conversation when they ask you, "Can I bring the kids/boyfriend I met last week?".</p>

		<p class="last">If you don't personalise your wedding invitations with individual names, it's not clear who exactly is invited--and that means more hassle for you.</p>















































				<h2 class="text_center width_medium">
								 <img src="/images/homepage/icons/pig-with-round-tail.svg" class="icon blocked_and_centred" /><br/>
																			Don't let your invitation look like a card from Moonpig&hellip;

																		</h2>
		<p class="quarter_padding_vertical">

			Whatever you do, please, please don't let your invitation look like it was created in Microsoft Word.
		</p>

		<p class="quarter_padding_vertical">
			Nothing shouts cheap and amateur louder and looks uglier than an invitation that's been laid out by someone with no typography skills. </p>
		<p class="quarter_padding_vertical">
			There's a reason people hire graphic designersâ¦</p>
		<p class="quarter_padding_vertical">
			â¦sometimes when you look at something, it just looks professional, chic and expensive but if anyone was to ask you, you wouldn't be able to explain why--it's just a feeling.</p>


		<p class="quarter_padding_vertical">
			But a lot of work goes into making you have that feeling: it's all in the detail-- care and attention to the little nuances that, on their own don't seem very significant but combined make a massive difference to the way people see and perceive your invitations--either
			as cheap and tacky or expensive and elegant.</p>

		<p class="quarter_padding_vertical">Subtle touches such as careful alignment and spacing, the use of bullet points and ornamental separations between paragraphs are just some of the things that individually may not sound like much but together add up to create a stunning layout that you
			would expect from a Royal wedding.</p>


		<p class="quarter_padding_vertical">Stuff from Lidl looks and feels cheaper than the premium products at Waitrose. </p>

		<h2 class="width_small text_center font_smaller">The Sun newspaper looks tackier and less classy than The Times. </h2>

		<p class="quarter_padding_vertical">But whilst you can see the difference, it takes a professional to understand what goes into making the difference. </p>

		<p class="quarter_padding_vertical"> Free fonts and clipart that have been downloaded from the internet are free for a reason: they don't have the same refinements that will give your invitations a polished, superior look.</p>

		<img src="/images/homepage/big_illustrations/invitetext.png" class="image_100" style="display:block;margin:0 auto;" />


		<p class="quarter_padding_vertical">
			Some of the fonts we use have cost hundreds of pounds, and we pay that because we know the time and effort went into creating them and the value they give in making your invitations look exquisite. </p>
		<p class="quarter_padding_vertical">
			Too many stationery suppliers are often brides with no design background who've created their own stationery and decided to make a bit of money on the side creating stationery for others. </p>
		<p class="last">
			Which leads me nicely onto...</p>

































































				<h2 class="text_center width_small">
																														<img src="/images/homepage/icons/sound.svg" style="width:40px;display:inline-block" /><br/>
												Substance is as important as style&hellip;
											</h2>


		<p class="quarter_padding_vertical">
			It's important for your invitations to look good: there's no doubt about that.</p>

		<p class="quarter_padding_vertical">
			But it's only half the battle: caught up in the delight of making sure everything looks perfect, it's very easy to forget that invitations serve a practical function too: to inform and educate your guests as much as possible about the event, and in turn,
			to make planning your wedding easier and therefore less stressful for you.

		</p>
		<p class="quarter_padding_vertical">

			To do that, you need to think of all the possible questions your guests are going to have and try to answer them in the content of your invitation.

		</p>
		<p class="quarter_padding_vertical">
			You're also going to need to figure out what information you're going to need back from them to help you plan your wedding, such as simple RSVPs for guest numbers and things like menu choices.

		</p>
		<p class="quarter_padding_vertical">
			Your guests are human, and like most humans, they're more likely to do something if it's easy and pain-free, so you also need to make it as easy as possible for them to reply.

		</p>
		<p class="quarter_padding_vertical">
			That's why those little extras, such as information enclosures and reply cards are important.

		</p>
		<p class="quarter_padding_vertical">
			A pre-addressed reply card increases your chances of getting responses quickly as it is very easy for your guests to just tick a box or two and post the card.

		</p>
		<p class="quarter_padding_vertical">
			We even print your guest names on the reply cards to make it even easier for them (and more accurate for you&mdash;leave it to your guests and believe me they won't even remember to write their own name so you won't know who the reply card is from!).

		</p>
		<p class="quarter_padding_vertical">
			No reply cards means no replies: and no replies means, among the other 101 things you need to do, you're going to have the hassle of chasing your guests to find out who is, or isn't, coming.

		</p>
		<p class="quarter_padding_vertical">
			In our experience, invitations with reply cards get around three times as many responses as invitations without!

		</p>
		<p class="quarter_padding_vertical">
			You'll find the number of details you provide about your wedding day is inversely proportional to the stress you'll experience (the more details you give, less stress for you!).

		</p>
		<p class="quarter_padding_vertical">
			That's why providing an additional instruction leaflet for all the extra stuff can really make your life easierso guests don't have to hassle you with questions at the last minute:

		</p>
		<p class="quarter_padding_vertical">
			Where exactly is the venue?

		</p>
		<p class="quarter_padding_vertical">
			A simple map can save you and your bridesmaids dealing with the exasperation of answering twenty phone calls on the morning of your wedding as lost guests phone you when they've gone up the wrong country lane.

		</p>
		<p class="quarter_padding_vertical">
			What do they wear?

		</p>
		<p class="quarter_padding_vertical">
			Explaining the dress code is important if you don't want Auntie Edna turning up in that bright puce dress with the ostentatious hat.

		</p>
		<p class="quarter_padding_vertical">
			Can children come?

		</p>
		<p class="quarter_padding_vertical">
			Can they give vouchers or money instead of buying you another garlic press?

		</p>
		<p class="quarter_padding_vertical">
			It's monotonous and rage-inducing to keep hearing the same questions again and again: avoid the bitterness by answering questions in advance with a comprehensive information enclosure.

		</p>

